My work has a lot to do with researching health related issues and making natural discoveries.

Psoriasis is a skin related disease and the kiva community out I've listed the "triggers" for it.

Psoriasis Triggers

A majority of individuals living with psoriasis experience bad days when psoriasis flares and good days when their skin clears. Usually, a trigger is needed for psoriasis to appear. Common triggers of psoriasis are:
Weather
Cold weather is known to be a common trigger for numerous people and sunny and hot climates seem to clear the skin.
Stress
Psoriasis can flare as a result of stress.
Skin Injury
Psoriasis is capable of appearing in areas of the skin that have been traumatized or injured. Koebner response can be triggered by scratches, sunburns and vaccinations.
Medications
Some medications can trigger psoriasis. Among others, they include:

Indomethacin
Lithium
Inderal
Antimalarials
Quinidine


Infection
Some infections may trigger psoriasis. Oftentimes, strep throat predates an irruption of guttate psoriasis. A thrush infection can aggravate inverse psoriasis. Psoriasis can be triggered by several infections:

Viral upper respiratory condition
Human immunodeficiency virus (HIV)
Candida albicans (thrush)
Streptococcal pharyngitis (strep throat)
Staphylococcal skin infections (boils)


Other triggers
Although not proven scientifically, some people suffering from psoriasis suspect that diet and allergies trigger their psoriasis.
